  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a criminal offense under legislation in most countries. Specifically:\n\n1. Money laundering is typically classified as a serious criminal offense in:\n- Criminal codes\n- Anti-money laundering (AML) laws\n- Financial crime statutes\n\n2. Key characteristics of money laundering as a criminal activity:\n- Involves concealing the origins of illegally obtained money\n- Transforms \"dirty\" money from illegal activities into seemingly \"clean\" funds\n- Considered a financial crime with potential severe legal penalties\n\n3. Legal consequences often include:\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Substantial fines\n- Potential imprisonment\n- Asset seizure\n\n4. Many countries have specific legislation addressing money laundering, such as:\n- United States: Bank Secrecy Act\n- United Kingdom: Proceeds of Crime Act\n- International standards set by Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n\n5. Money laundering is often associated with other criminal activities like:\n- Drug trafficking\n- Fraud\n- Organized crime\n- Terrorism financing\n\nThe specific legal treatment can vary between jurisdictions, but it is universally recognized as a criminal offense with serious legal implications.",
